    <h1>SLB N.V. (SLB)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of SLB N.V. (formerly Schlumberger) — using FY2025 actuals, disclosed assumptions, and one final number.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated March 18, 2026 · Data: FY2025 Financials</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$35.7B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2025 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$4.5B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$2.35</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">15.3%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">${(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash (Debt)</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>SLB generated <strong>$4.54 billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2025. This is operating cash flow ($6.49B) minus capital expenditures ($1.95B). This represents real cash the business produces after reinvesting in its global oilfield services operations.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We project FCF to grow at <strong>5% per year</strong> for the next 5 years. While revenue dipped slightly in FY2025, long-term offshore development and international cycle dynamics support moderate but steady growth in service contracts and margins.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>2% forever</strong>. This is below historical GDP growth, reflecting the long-term realities of the energy transition, while acknowledging that oil and gas will remain a significant part of the global energy mix for decades.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>9%</strong>. For a mature, cyclical industrial/services company with a beta of 0.71 and a strong balance sheet, a 9% WACC provides a solid required return relative to the 10Y Treasury (4.18%).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value minus Net Debt ($8.2B) = Equity Value. Divide by shares outstanding (1.50B) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        SLB's revenue growth has moderated, but free cash flow remains exceptionally strong ($4.5B run rate). Given the company's pivot to higher-margin digital and offshore services, 5% FCF growth represents steady operational execution without assuming an aggressive new oil supercycle.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">9%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        With the 10Y Treasury at 4.18% and SLB's beta at 0.71, CAPM suggests a lower cost of equity. However, given the inherent cyclicality of energy markets, applying a 9% discount rate provides an appropriate margin of safety for the cyclical risk.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        2% is slightly below long-term nominal GDP growth. This reflects the gradual, multi-decade transition away from fossil fuels, recognizing that while terminal growth is capped, SLB's critical role in maintaining existing global energy infrastructure ensures long-term cash generation.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
