  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Extended Upcycle:</strong> If geopolitical tensions or chronic underinvestment in supply lead to structurally higher oil prices, international offshore and Middle East activity could trigger an extended upcycle beyond our 5% forecast.</li>
    <li><strong>Digital Margins:</strong> Faster adoption of SLB's high-margin digital and AI-driven subsurface software platforms could drastically lift operating margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Shareholder Returns:</strong> Aggressive share repurchases beyond our static share count could rapidly increase intrinsic value per share.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Commodity Price Crashes:</strong> A sudden drop in global oil demand (e.g., severe recession) would cause E&P companies to immediately slash capital expenditure budgets, severely impacting SLB's revenue.</li>
    <li><strong>Accelerated Energy Transition:</strong> If global policy mandates force a faster-than-expected phase-out of fossil fuels, terminal growth could turn negative.</li>
    <li><strong>Geopolitical Headwinds:</strong> Operations in sensitive regions (like Russia and the Middle East) expose the company to significant sanctions and operational risks.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E or EV/EBITDA multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples tell you what the market <em>is</em> paying — not what a company is <em>worth</em>. A DCF forces you to state explicit assumptions about growth and risk, then lets math determine the price. It's the only valuation method that directly connects cash flow generation to value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 9% discount rate for a cyclical business?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While energy services are cyclical, SLB's size, global diversification, and low beta (0.71) help buffer extreme volatility compared to smaller E&P operators. A 9% WACC adequately accounts for the underlying macro risks while reflecting their dominant market position and strong balance sheet.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is terminal growth capped at 2%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Even though SLB continues to grow its new energy and digital segments, the bulk of its business is tied to traditional oil and gas. Capping terminal growth at 2% conservatively reflects the inevitable multi-decade maturation of the fossil fuel industry.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

